# StakMesh cluster launcher config.
#
# Copy this file to cluster_nodes.conf (gitignored - it'll have your real
# IPs/usernames/paths) and fill in your machines. One line per rank, two
# possible formats:
#
#   <rank> local <command>
#   <rank> ssh <user@host> <command>
#
# `command` is exactly what you'd normally type on that machine by hand to
# start training. Whatever extra args you pass to launch_cluster.sh after
# `--` get appended to EVERY rank's command automatically, so you don't
# have to hardcode --epochs/--batch-size here:
#
#   ./scripts/launch_cluster.sh -- --epochs 5 --batch-size 512
#
# ── Example setup (Linux control machine + Windows second rank) ──
#
# Rank 0 (this machine, Linux) runs directly - no ssh needed since the
# script itself runs here.
#
# Rank 1 (the Windows machine) runs over ssh. Two things to get right on the
# Windows side before this works:
#
#   1. OpenSSH Server must be enabled and running:
#        Settings -> Apps -> Optional Features -> Add a feature -> OpenSSH Server
#        (or:  Add-WindowsCapability -Online -Name OpenSSH.Server~~~~0.0.1.0
#         then  Start-Service sshd ; Set-Service -Name sshd -StartupType Automatic)
#      Test it works BEFORE trying this script:
#        ssh <user>@<windows-hostname>
#
#   2. Know which shell your ssh session drops you into - matters a lot,
#      since cmd.exe and PowerShell have incompatible syntax (";" vs "&&"
#      for chaining, and PowerShell needs ".\" before a bare .exe name -
#      it never searches the current directory, unlike cmd.exe). Check:
#        ssh <user>@<windows-hostname> "$PSVersionTable"
#      Prints a version table -> PowerShell. Prints an error like
#      "'$PSVersionTable' is not recognized" -> cmd.exe.
#
#      The example below assumes PowerShell (";" chaining, ".\" prefix) -
#      the safer default, since it works whether you're on Windows
#      PowerShell 5.1 or PowerShell 7+ ("&&" only works on 7+). If you
#      confirmed cmd.exe above, switch to: cd <path> && mnist_distributed.exe ...

0 local cd ~/StakMesh/build && ./mnist_distributed --config ../configs/two_laptop_cluster.local.txt

1 ssh <user>@<windows-hostname> cd C:\path\to\StakMesh\build ; .\mnist_distributed.exe --config ../configs/two_laptop_cluster.local.txt

# ── Optional: skip building on the remote entirely ──
#
# Add one "<rank> deploy <local-binary> <remote-dest>" line per remote rank,
# then run `./launch_cluster.sh --deploy -- ...` instead of the plain form.
# Before any rank starts, this scp's <local-binary> to <remote-dest> on that
# rank's ssh target (host comes from the matching "ssh" line above, so you
# don't repeat it here). <local-binary> can be your own build/mnist_distributed,
# or a binary pulled from a CI run (.github/workflows/build-binaries.yml) -
# either way, no clone or compiler needed on the remote machine.
#
# 1 deploy ../build/mnist_distributed.exe C:\path\to\StakMesh\build\mnist_distributed.exe